<methodology slug="value-proposition-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Design a compelling value proposition using the Value Proposition Canvas: map customer jobs, pains, and gains against your product's relievers and gain creators to achieve product-market fit.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>value-proposition</tag>
      <tag>positioning</tag>
      <tag>canvas</tag>
      <tag>customer-research</tag>
      <tag>product-market-fit</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Value Proposition Design</title>

    <summary>Value Proposition Design answers "Why should I choose you over alternatives?" by mapping customer jobs, pains, and gains against your product's pain relievers and gain creators using the Value Proposition Canvas. The canvas is a two-sided diagram (customer profile vs. value map) that reveals alignment gaps and guides positioning, messaging, and feature prioritization.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Products fail because they don't clearly articulate why someone should buy. Feature lists instead of benefits, identical messaging to competitors, unclear value to target audiences, and misalignment between offer and customer needs are the root causes. A systematic process for designing compelling value propositions prevents these failures.</p>
      <p>The Value Proposition Canvas forces explicit agreement between teams on what pains the product solves, what gains it creates, and how strongly those map to actual customer needs. Without this discipline, companies ship features customers don't value while missing the jobs and pains that matter most.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch: drafting positioning before landing-page copy, ad copy, or sales decks.</item>
        <item>Repositioning: when conversion is low and copy reads generic ("AI-powered platform for businesses").</item>
        <item>New segment expansion: same product, new audience needs a new value prop.</item>
        <item>Competitive shift: a major competitor changes pricing or positioning and you must respond.</item>
        <item>Low market traction or weak product adoption despite feature completeness.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before talking to users: you'll guess pains and gains without evidence.</item>
        <item>For mature products with established positioning where the cost of churn from rebrand is high.</item>
        <item>For internal tools where the "value" question is irrelevant.</item>
        <item>As a substitute for messaging tests: the canvas is a draft, not final positioning.</item>
        <item>When no primary customer research exists (interviews, JTBD studies, personas): the canvas requires validated inputs.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="value-proposition-canvas-framework">
      <p>The Value Proposition Canvas is a two-by-three grid from Strategyzer that aligns customer needs with product capabilities.</p>

      <p>The top half is the Customer Profile: what jobs the customer tries to accomplish, what pains block them, and what gains they desire.</p>

      <p>The bottom half is the Value Map: what products and services you offer, how you relieve pains, and how you create gains.</p>

      <p>Fit occurs where the Value Map directly addresses the pains and creates the gains mapped in the Customer Profile. No fit means the product misses customer priorities.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Build the Customer Profile first, in full, BEFORE thinking about your product. This prevents reverse-engineering pains to fit features.</statement>
        <rationale>Product-first thinking leads to feature-led value propositions that ignore customer reality. Customer-first thinking surfaces what actually matters; you then design the product to address it.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="customer-profile-mapping">
      <p>The Customer Profile has three pillars: jobs, pains, gains.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Map customer jobs across three dimensions: functional (what they try to get done), emotional (how they want to feel), and social (how they want to be perceived). Every job must come from research, not assumption.</statement>
        <rationale>Functional jobs are necessary but not sufficient for positioning. Emotional and social jobs often drive purchase decisions more than capability. Research validates that these jobs are real; agents guessing jobs produce fiction.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Well-researched customer jobs">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Functional jobs:
- File taxes annually with minimal complexity
- Organize receipts and expense tracking
- Generate reports for accountant review

Emotional jobs:
- Feel in control of finances
- Reduce anxiety about tax season
- Trust the numbers are correct

Social jobs:
- Look financially literate to accountant
- Demonstrate business professionalism
]]></code>
        <note>Each job comes from customer interviews; not guessed from competitor positioning.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Guessed jobs without research">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Jobs:
- Use AI-powered tax filing
- Access real-time analytics
- Integrate with cloud platforms
]]></code>
        <note>These are features, not jobs. No evidence these are priorities to customers.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>For each pain, record severity (extreme / moderate / minor), frequency, and the specific obstacle or undesired outcome the customer faces. Extreme pains are must-solve; minor pains are nice-to-solve. Build relief strategies proportional to severity.</statement>
        <rationale>Overemphasizing minor pains wastes product effort. Severity distribution also guides messaging: extreme pains belong in headlines, moderate pains in supporting copy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Pain categories and severity">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Pains:

Undesired outcomes:
- Takes too long to collect receipts (moderate, daily)
- Cost of accountant time is high (extreme, annual)

Obstacles:
- Can't figure out which expenses are deductible (moderate, ongoing)
- No budget to hire bookkeeper (extreme, chronic)

Risks:
- Might miss deductions and overpay (extreme, annual)
- Could trigger tax audit if records are disorganized (extreme, rare)
]]></code>
        <note>Severity and frequency inform feature prioritization and copy emphasis.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>For gains, distinguish between required (minimum expectation), expected (standard for category), desired (would love to have), and unexpected (delightful surprise). Required and expected gains are table stakes; differentiation lives in desired and unexpected gains.</statement>
        <rationale>Every gain is not equal. Required/expected gains prevent dissatisfaction but don't drive choice. Desired/unexpected gains are what customers compare when choosing between similar products.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="value-map-design">
      <p>The Value Map translates customer jobs/pains/gains into your product offerings.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>For each mapped pain, explicitly state how your product eliminates or reduces it. Do not list features; describe the outcome the customer experiences. "Automatic receipt capture via OCR" is a feature; "uploads receipts in 10 seconds instead of 5 minutes of manual typing" is an outcome.</statement>
        <rationale>Feature-led copy leads with capability instead of benefit. Outcome-led copy connects the feature to the customer's pain. This prevents feature-leak where the value prop reads as a laundry list of technical capabilities.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Pain reliever with outcome focus">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Pain: Can't figure out which expenses are deductible
Product capability: AI-powered categorization engine
Pain reliever: Every receipt is automatically categorized by tax code and deductibility rule
Outcome: No more guessing; confidence that you're not missing deductions or claiming invalid ones
Relief level: Complete
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Feature-led pain reliever">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Pain reliever: Machine learning-based expense categorization

[This reads as a feature. Customer doesn't care about ML; customer cares about confidence.]
]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>For each gain, describe how your product creates it. Every Gain Creator must tie to a specific product feature. If you can't name the feature, the gain is aspirational, not deliverable.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents over-promise on gains when no feature backs the claim. Feature traceability prevents fiction in the value prop.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Anchor each Pain Reliever and Gain Creator to a specific product feature. If you list ten pain relievers but have five features, you have a positioning problem. One feature can relieve multiple pains; one pain is not solved by ten features.</statement>
        <rationale>Feature-to-pain/gain mapping reveals where the product is over-promising or under-delivering. Sparse reliever-to-feature mapping is a design failure; it means features aren't being leveraged strategically.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="fit-assessment">
      <rule>
        <statement>Score fit across jobs (do you address real jobs?), pains relieved (which pains are addressed? which are missed?), and gains created (which gains are delivered?). No single score; map each reliever and gain creator to the customer profile dimensions. Acknowledge gaps explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>Fit is multidimensional, not a single number. A product might solve extreme pains perfectly but miss desired gains entirely. Honest gap analysis guides feature prioritization and messaging focus.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Fit assessment with explicit gaps">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Fit Assessment: Tax Filing App

Jobs addressed:
- Functional: 90% (filing + organizing, not accounting consultation)
- Emotional: 70% (reduces anxiety about filing, but not about audit risk)
- Social: 0% (doesn't help look competent to others)

Pains relieved:
- Time (solved, extreme pain)
- Cost (partially, moderate pain)
- Uncertainty (solved, extreme pain)
- Audit risk (not addressed, extreme pain)

Gains created:
- Simple process (delivered, expected gain)
- Confidence (delivered, desired gain)
- Professional appearance (not delivered, desired gain)

Gaps: Audit insurance, consultation on edge cases, professional presentation to accountant.
Opportunities: Partner integrations (insurance, consultation) could close social job gap.
]]></code>
        <note>Honest assessment reveals where product shines and where competitors win.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="value-proposition-statement">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write a positioning statement using the template: "For [target customer] who [job/need] [Product name] is a [category] that [key benefit] Unlike [alternative] We [key differentiator]." The statement must name a specific alternative and a measurable claim, not vague superiority.</statement>
        <rationale>The template forces explicitness. Vague positioning ("more user-friendly," "innovative") is unmemorable and untestable. Specific claims are memorable and credible.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Strong positioning statement">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
For independent writers
Who want to grow and monetize their newsletter
NewsletterKit is an email platform
That stays affordable as you scale
Unlike Substack (per-subscriber pricing) or ConvertKit (enterprise minimums)
We charge flat $29/month regardless of list size
]]></code>
        <note>Specific alternative, specific claim, memorable ratio.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Vague positioning">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
For writers
NewsletterKit is an AI-powered platform
That makes email easier
Unlike others
We are innovative
]]></code>
        <note>No specific customer, no alternative, no claim. Unmemorable.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test 3-5 headline variants on cold traffic; intuition is unreliable for which positioning resonates. Run A/B tests on landing pages or Twitter ads; measure click-through and sign-up rate per variant. Pick the winner, not the variant you like.</statement>
        <rationale>Positioning designed by committees produces lowest-common-denominator copy. Positioning tested on real customers reveals what actually moves behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Building the canvas around features instead of customer jobs, pains, and gains.</description>
        <reason>The canvas becomes a product datasheet. Without customer-first framing, you miss what customers actually care about and build a feature list instead of value prop.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Creating one generic value prop that "works for everyone."</description>
        <reason>One value prop per segment. Positioning that fits everyone fits no one. Explicit audience segmentation allows targeted positioning per segment.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Designing pain relievers and gain creators without research data on customer problems and desires.</description>
        <reason>The canvas becomes fiction. Every entry must cite interview data or JTBD research. Agents guessing pains produce plausible-sounding but untested hypotheses.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading with the product category or feature in the value prop ("AI-powered platform," "blockchain-based solution").</description>
        <reason>Customers don't buy categories or technologies; they buy outcomes. Feature-led copy reads as marketing jargon, not value.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Equating "Unlike X" with a real differentiator ("more user-friendly," "better support").</description>
        <reason>Weak differentiators. Every product claims to be user-friendly. Differentiators must be measurable, specific, and hard to copy ("flat pricing regardless of scale," "offline-first sync").</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Refreshing the value prop once and leaving it static.</description>
        <reason>Markets move. Yesterday's differentiator becomes table stakes. Quarterly refresh keeps positioning sharp; annual refresh is minimum discipline.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Three-stage pipeline: (1) ingest validated research (interviews, JTBD, persona) and extract Customer Profile (jobs/pains/gains), (2) draft Value Map (products/relievers/creators), (3) check fit and produce a positioning statement plus 3 testable headline variants. Run a separate "feature-leak detector" pass to flag value-prop drafts that read as feature lists. Human picks final headline; agent ships variants.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Require every canvas entry to cite research: interview IDs, JTBD codes, or persona source. Refuse to generate canvas without research input. Agents filling the canvas from inference produce fiction.</statement>
        <rationale>The canvas is a research translation tool, not a generation tool. Without citations, the agent is guessing, not discovering.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run a feature-leak detector pass on drafted headlines and benefits. Flag any that lead with feature ("uses AI," "API-based," "with real-time") and suggest outcome-led rewrites. Require all flags resolved before outputting final positioning.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs default to feature-led copy. A linter pass catches this before human review.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Force a distribution constraint on pain severity: max 30% extreme, 40% moderate, 30% minor. Agents over-report severity; this constraint pushes realistic prioritization.</statement>
        <rationale>Every pain isn't extreme. Realistic distributions guide where to spend product effort.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Force at least one desired or unexpected gain in the gains list. Agents collapse gains to expected; at least one differentiation-worthy gain pushes positioning thinking.</statement>
        <rationale>Expected gains are table stakes. Desired/unexpected gains are where products differentiate.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

